<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Zinc concentrates shortage
forecast
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TODAY'S HUGE surplus of zinc concentrates, the raw material used by
smelters, will swing into a big shortfall in the next two to three years,
warns a study by consultants Brook Hunt &amp; Associates.
The shortfall could rise to 1.2m tonnes by 2000 and 2.8m tonnes in 2005.
Brook Hunt says the problem is being caused by today's low prices and
smelters' high treatment charges which have made about half the western
world zinc mine capacity uneconomic and caused the closure so far in 1993 of
400,000 tonnes of mine capacity.
The study identifies those smelters that might lose their concentrate
supplies because of mine closures and says several companies which today
rely on their own mines may be forced into the custom concentrate market in
future.
The Zinc Concentrate Market to 2005. Pounds 8,000 from Brook Hunt, 11 London
Street, Chertsey, Surrey, KT16 8AP, UK.
</TEXT>
