FT  13 MAY 93 / International Company News: Ortiz posts sharp decline in
earnings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ORTIZ, the French food group behind Miko ice cream, suffered a rapid decline
in net profits to FFr12.7m (Dollars 2.35m) in 1992 from FFr53.5m in 1991
because of the squeeze on consumer spending.
The group, which produces Vivagel delicatessen products, has, like other
food companies, been badly affected by high interest rates and rising
unemployment on the French consumer goods market.
Consolidated sales fell by 1 per cent to FFr5.31bn in 1992 from FFr5.38bn in
1991. The 1992 figures were also affected by a number of structural changes
within the group.
Ortiz said net profits had been depressed by heavy marketing expenditure for
both the Miko and Vivagel brands and the cost of reorganising its
distribution system.
Ortiz said that, in spite of the fall in 1992 profits, it was confident
about its future prospects, notably because of the impact of the cost
cutting implemented in 1992, which should have a positive effect on this
year's results.
Canadian-based John Labatt has sold the Tuscan division of Johanna Farms to
Dairy Enterprises. The purchase price and other details of the transaction
were not disclosed, Reuter reports from Toronto.
The Tuscan dairy division consists of Tuscan Industries in New Jersey and
New York, which operates out of two plants and employs 660.
Dairy Enterprises is a newly formed company in which James Schreiber,
Michael Marcus and affiliates of the Steinhardt Organisation are investors.
