<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 93 / Italian public sector chief charged: Iri state group
chairman linked to illicit political funding scandal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Franco Nobili, chairman of Iri, Italy's biggest state holding company,
was yesterday arrested by Milan magistrates and transferred to the city's
San Vittore jail on charges of corruption.
Mr Nobili, 62, holds the most prominent position in the Italian public
sector. Until now, the Iri group has only figured in a minor way in the
15-month investigations by Milan magistrates into illicit funding of the
political parties, mainly through kickbacks paid on contracts.
The chief executives of the Italian subsidiaries of two foreign companies
operating in the lucrative telecommunications sector - Sweden's Ericsson and
the UK's GEC - were also arrested on charges of alleged corruption. The
arrests relate to a developing line of inquiry by Milan magistrates into
kickbacks allegedly paid for a share in Italy's large telecommunications
sector.
Mr Nobili has been Iri chairman since 1990, having been appointed to this
post, traditionally controlled by the Christian Democrat party, by his
friend Mr Giulio Andreotti, who was then prime minister.
The operations of Iri are unlikely to be affected since Mr Nobili was
effectively forced into a representational role last August when Iri's
status was changed to a joint stock company. The running of Iri and
strategic planning has been in the hands of Mr Michele Tedeschi, the
managing director.
Within the past two months, the management of the country's three main
state-run industrial groups have all become implicated in the corruption
scandals.
In March, Mr Gabriele Cagliari, the chairman of Eni, the state oil concern,
was arrested along with the heads of the group's four main subsidiaries on
charges of allegedly falsifying accounts. Since then, a complex picture of
illicit funding of political parties, has emerged from Eni companies,
believed to have been worth L27bn (Pounds 11.5m) since 1989. At the same
time, Mr Mauro Leone, deputy chairman of Efim, the industrial holding placed
in liquidation last July, was arrested on charges of alleged fraud. The
allegations of corruption in Mr Nobili's case are understood to refer both
to his time as Iri chairman and during the period from 1978-89 when he ran
Cogefar, a leading construction company.
The magistrates are reportedly mainly concerned with his activities in
Cogefar, before its merger with Fiat's Impresit in 1989. The alleged payment
of bribes by Cogefar-Impresit to obtain contracts has been the main account
on which magistrates have been questioning Fiat executives over the past
year.
Mr Nobili's arrest is linked to a fresh questioning of Mr Enzo Papi, former
managing director of Cogefar-Impresit, arrested last May and held for 55
days before admitting the payment of bribes.
Page 2
Fiat's code of ethics
Senate confidence vote
</TEXT>
<XX>
