<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: Scottish Tories meet in upbeat mood
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH CONSERVATIVES gathering in Edinburgh yesterday were more cheerful
than they usually are on the first day of their party conference.
Usually the mood on the first day is nervous and tentative, with delegates
conscious of being an unpopular minority which does badly in elections.
But after last year's general election in which, against all predictions,
the Tories won two seats and slightly increased their share of the vote in
Scotland, there was a feeling that they were no longer an imperilled
species.
They found it difficult to comprehend fully the scale of anxiety sweeping
their party at Westminster after the Newbury by-election and the drubbing
the Tories suffered in the county council elections. There were no local
elections last week in Scotland.
For the first time in years a Conservative administration at the Scottish
Office is not looking beleaguered. Mr Ian Lang, the Scottish secretary,
enjoys apparently effortless supremacy over his opponents in the Commons.
The political storms which have shaken the government have largely passed
Scotland by. Scotland has suffered recession, but not nearly as badly as the
south. Its unemployment rate is still 9.6 per cent but, unprecedentedly,
that is lower than in any other region of the UK except East Anglia.
Yet important warnings were delivered to the ministers sitting on the
platform yesterday.
Apart from disquiet over Scottish water, speakers complained about the
imposition of value added tax on home heating bills in the Budget, and on
changes to petroleum revenue tax which are likely to reduce spending on
exploration in the North Sea.
Mr Adrian Shinwell, Scottish Conservative and Unionist Association
president, referred to these criticisms when he said: 'There are certain
policies and proposals which have caused disquiet among our membership, and
as your president I would be failing in my responsibilities if I sought to
deny that or ignore it.'
The VAT increase will particularly affect Scotland because of its cold
climate, while north-east Scotland depends heavily on the North Sea oil
industry.
Mr John Young, a Tory councillor from Glasgow, pointed out that the first 8
per cent tranche of the imposition of VAT would come next year just before
elections for the European parliament, in which there are no Scottish Tory
MPs.
The second tranche would come the following year when elections might be
held for new single-tier councils.
</TEXT>
