<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: Labour slams 'sneaky' tax rises
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'SNEAKY' TAX increases such as the freezing of personal allowances and the
limiting to 20 per cent of tax relief on mortgage interest will yield the
Treasury as much as Pounds 2.7bn in 1995/96, Labour said yesterday, David
Owen writes.
As the Finance Bill implementing the spring Budget started its third day in
committee, Mr Nick Brown, a Labour frontbench Treasury spokesman, accused
the government of 'scouring the Treasury files' for ways of raising taxes
without anybody noticing.
Mr Brown argued that Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, hoped people would
not notice the tax relief adjustments because mortgage rates had come down.
Labour objected 'very strongly' to the government's enactment of tax changes
that were 'noticeably regressive.'
There was support for Labour's stance from Mr Alan Beith, the Liberal
Democrat Treasury spokesman, who argued that the government's extension of
the 20 per cent band of income tax was not a measure to help the lowest paid
but to raise more revenue.
Mr Stephen Dorrell, financial secretary to the Treasury, retorted that
allowances should not be looked at in isolation from other Budget changes.
The additional burden to be imposed by the Budget package was being 'fairly
shared' right across the income scale.
A Labour amendment clearing the way for personal allowances to be uprated in
line with inflation was defeated by 277 votes to 236, a government majority
of 41.
</TEXT>
