FT  13 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: Review to consider structure of NHS
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ability of the National Health Service management structure to satisfy
the requirements of public accountability are to be examined in a review
announced by Mrs Virginia Bottomley, health secretary, yesterday.
The review, due to be completed by July, will take place at a time when MPs
are raising severely critical questions about mismanagement and mishandling
of public money in parts of the service.
Mrs Bottomley said in February that she was reviewing NHS structure above
local level, to ensure that the internal market introduced by the 1991
reforms was able to work to full effect. Since then, however, highly
publicised financial problems have added to pressure on the health secretary
to widen the scope of the review.
Sir Duncan Nichol, NHS chief executive, has faced critical questioning from
the Commons public accounts committee over inadequate management controls in
the West Midlands and Wessex regional health authorities. The committee has
been told that management problems in the West Midlands led to expenditure
of at least Pounds 10m for which little or no value was received, while in
Wessex at least Pounds 20m was wasted. Four people face conspiracy to
defraud charges arising from Wessex computer contracts.
</TEXT>
