<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: Ashdown rules out pact with Labour
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR PADDY ASHDOWN, leader of the Liberal Democrats, yesterday stepped up the
pressure on Labour leaders to accept that their party has little prospect of
winning the next general election on its own.
He again ruled out any formal pact with Labour, and left open the door for
co-operation with the Conservative party should a continuing decline in its
electoral fortunes open the way for a broad-based coalition.
Highlighting the key lesson of the outstanding success achieved by the
Liberal Democrats when Mr David Rendel captured Newbury from the
Conservatives in last week's by-election, he said the results showed that
'we reach the votes that the Labour party cannot reach'.
Responding to questions at a Parliamentary press gallery lunch, he refused
say whether his party would be more likely to support a government led by Mr
John Major for the Conservatives or by Mr John Smith for Labour.
He said that without knowing the political climate before the next general
election it was impossible to make that kind of prediction.
Mr Ashdown warned the Liberal Democrats against 'triumphalism' in the wake
of the successes achieved at Newbury and in the county council elections.
He called on the 'modernisers' in the Labour party to gain the upper hand by
ending its domination by the trade unions through the introduction of one
member, one vote, and securing support for ending the first-past-the-post
electoral system.
He suggested that the need for co-operation between the parties at local
level in councils where no single party had a majority could set a pattern
leading to 'partnership in power' nationally.
Mr John Smith, Labour leader, had a foretaste yesterday of the scale of
opposition within his party to electoral reform.
At a private Parliamentary Labour party meeting, MPs were divided over the
conclusions of Labour's internal inquiry into electoral reform under
Professor Raymond Plant of Southampton University.
Mr Smith is expected to say next Wednesday that Labour must back the
principle of change - but will try to unite his party around a pledge that
reforms will depend on winning approval in a national referendum.
</TEXT>
