<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: Ministers defend bus deregulation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRANSPORT ministers yesterday launched a spirited defence of their proposals
to deregulate London's bus services - and rejected widespread criticism from
local authorities and London transport that the move will lead to road
congestion and fare rises in the capital.
Mr Steven Norris, minister for transport in London, told the transport
committee that plans for deregulation would proceed in spite of the
criticism, since this was the only way 'to offer the services people want'.
The government intends to introduce the issue into the next parliamentary
session, to bring London into line with bus services outside the capital,
which were deregulated in the mid 1980s.
Nevertheless, responding to criticism that bus deregulation elsewhere had
contributed to road congestion and falling numbers of bus passengers, Mr
Roger Freeman, the transport minister, conceded that some fine-tuning might
be necessary in the future.
Traffic commissioners and Local Authorities could be given greater powers to
prevent over-congestion on profitable routes. At the same time, the level of
funding for 'bus priority measures', such as special bus lanes, would be
raised.
He insisted that 'social reasons', rather than deregulation, had been the
main reason for the falling number of bus passengers in the past.
</TEXT>
