<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: NatWest claims curb on job losses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NATIONAL Westminster Bank has managed to avoid a large number of compulsory
redundancies among its 93,000 employees this year despite its intention to
shed 4,000 jobs, Lord Alexander, the bank's chairman, said yesterday.
Lord Alexander told the Commons employment committee that only 97 staff had
been made compulsorily redundant in the first four months of the year, and
another 221 had accepted voluntary redundancy. Other jobs were being lost
through natural wastage.
He said that the net loss of 15,000 jobs between 1988 and last year had been
caused by a combination of technological change and the sharper than
expected dip into recession.
Lord Alexander said there had been 'negligible' recruitment of
school-leavers in the past three years as the bank tried to combat the surge
in its recruitment in the late 1980s.
The bank disclosed that it anticipated a cut of 25 per cent - from 815m to
602m - in the number of cheques it will clear this year compared to 1988.
Lord Alexander said the switch towards electronic forms of payment was
eliminating jobs.
Mr Leif Mills, general secretary of the Banking, Insurance and Finance
Union, said that NatWest had made 1,500 staff compulsorily redundant last
year, but unions had reached an agreement which would reduce the number this
year.
</TEXT>
