<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 93 / CBI seeks block on rise in pound
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR HOWARD DAVIES, director-general of the Confederation of British Industry,
last night urged the government not to let sterling gain in value and to cut
public spending.
Speaking at the annual dinner of the Institute of Materials in London, Mr
Davies said that UK financial conditions would have to be tightened as
economic recovery gained strength. To achieve this, the government could
either cut expenditure or let the pound rise.
Echoing widespread concern in industry about recent gains in sterling's
value, Mr Davies said allowing a further strengthening of sterling would be
'the wrong response' and would do nothing to correct the UK's large current
account balance-of-payments deficit. Mr Davies also called for a prolonged
period of 'lower interest rates' to stimulate investment.
However, in a separate report published today, the Chartered Institute of
Marketing said that business investment is proving to be one of the
strongest elements in Britain's economic recovery.
It said there were signs that UK business investment would recover to 16 per
cent of gross domestic product by 1995, which would be the third year of
recovery from recession. Following the 1979-81 recession, it took five years
for investment to reach that level.
The marketing institute forecast that by 1995 investment in Britain would
take a larger share of GDP than in the US or the other big European
countries.
However, it would still be well below the 20 per cent figure typical for
Japan or the 30 per cent to 35 per cent investment share of GDP recorded by
economies in south-east Asia.
Mr Douglas McWilliams, the institute's economic adviser, said that economic
recovery in Britain would continue slowly after a quick start. This would
mean a more sustainable recovery than in the 1980s.
But the recent improvement in the level of unemployment would not be
sustained and 'depressingly high unemployment levels' would remain for most
of this decade, he warned.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
