<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 93 / Formula for council funding attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CAMBRIDGE is more deprived than Hartlepool, if the government's assessment
of councils' spending needs is to be believed.
As a result the government pays Cambridge council more funds per head. This
is one of the most striking anomalies highlighted by the Audit Commission in
a report on standard spending assessments (SSAs) published today.
One of the effects, the commission says, is that 'neither central nor local
government accepts responsibility for decisions on particular services'.
Local authorities will have different SSAs according to their level of
deprivation. This is decided by a formula derived from the All Ages Social
Index, which takes into account how much various social factors (illustrated
in the graph) differ from the national average.
This is done in the interests of fairness. However, 'the complexity of the
formula hides underlying key political choices, obscuring decisions and who
makes them'.
The formula does not include economic factors such as the level of
unemployment in an area, because these factors do not impose direct spending
obligations on local authorities. The formula does, however, include social
and demographic factors that could increase spending because of deprivation.
These factors include the proportion of single-parent families and people
sharing accommodation, and the proportion of people with household heads
born in the New Commonwealth and Pakistan - this is, controversially, held
to be a sign of deprivation.
Cambridge's large number of students sharing accommodation and the low
proportion of immigrants in Hartlepool combine to produce the surprising
result that the north-eastern town is deemed to be less deprived.
The commission suggests that SSAs will need to be reformed but does not
support any particular alternative. It says the pressures on SSAs have
increased since they were introduced, because of four factors:
The 'gearing' effect of SSAs has increased because the proportion of local
authority expenditure coming from central government has increased from
about half to the current level of more than 80 per cent. This means that
small proportionate changes in SSAs have a bigger effect on local government
spending than they did before.
SSAs are now used by the government for 'capping' local authority budgets,
or limiting their expenditure, which increases their impact on a council's
spending decisions.
Pressure is growing for councils to set spending on each service according
to the SSA for that service. The government projects how much will be
earmarked for different services, but at present no restrictions are placed
on how councils apportion the total amount of money paid to them.
The Citizen's Charter intends using SSAs to compare the performance of
different councils.
Passing the Bucks: The Impact of SSAs on Economy, Efficiency, Effectiveness.
HMSO. Pounds 8.50.
</TEXT>
<XX>
