<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 93 / Squabble delays training revamp
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN OVERHAUL of the education and training of young people, which would
result in all 16-to-19-year-olds working towards a recognised qualification,
is being delayed by a squabble between government departments, the Training
and Enterprise Councils said yesterday, Diane Summers writes.
Tec leaders said that they had expected Mrs Gillian Shephard, employment
secretary, to publish a white paper on the issue this spring.
A working party - drawn from Tecs, the Department for Education, the
Employment Department and the Further Education Funding Council, submitted a
report to Mrs Shephard towards the end of last year, at her request.
The Engineering Employers' Federation yesterday urged a narrowing of the gap
between academic and vocational training, suggesting a new national
qualification that would be awarded to those who achieved three Level 3
National Vocational Qualifications, or three A-levels, or equivalent units
of AS examinations and/or vocational qualifications.
</TEXT>
