<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 93 / Pleas grow for late-bill interest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHAMBERS OF commerce yesterday added their voice to the lobby which is
calling for the government to give businesses a statutory right to interest
on unpaid bills.
This formed part of a package of measures intended to change the payment
culture of business announced by the Association of British Chambers of
Commerce at its annual conference in Leeds.
Mr Richard Brown, the chambers' policy director, said: 'The stubbornness and
complexity of the problem of late payment clearly indicate there is no
single simple solution. Every effort to tackle the problem must focus on
changing the payment culture.
'Consultation within the chamber of commerce movement has revealed that the
voluntary process of exhortation is not working.'
The chambers called for:
The compilation of 'white lists' of good payers which would be kept for
inspection in local chambers.
The extension of the requirement for large companies to disclose their
payment practices in their annual reports to cover all public limited
companies.
An investigation by the Lord Chancellor's department of the German system of
warnings to late payers which uses standard reminder forms and avoids full
court proceedings.
The requirement for sub-contractors on government contracts to pay their
suppliers within 30 days. At present only main contractors are expected to
do this. The 30-day requirement to be extended to contractors and
sub-contractors working for local authorities.
More funds for late payment advice 'hotlines', which should be developed
into a payment arbitration service.
The government has refused to introduce a statutory right to interest on
late payments, saying it would create more red tape.
For many years it relied on exhorting companies to pay on time but over the
past two years has funded pilot 'help-lines,' introduced a requirement -
still to be implemented - for large companies to report their payment
record, and simplified county court procedures for claiming debts.
The lobbying campaign for a statutory right to interest has been headed by
the Forum of Private Business, which has been joined by Intrum Justitia, a
debt collection company, and Dun &amp; Bradstreet, a business information group.
Recently support has come from two clearing banks, National Westminster and
Midland.
</TEXT>
