<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 93 / City police revise guidance on bombs
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
BUSINESSES IN the City must prepare for the constant threat of bombings such
as those at St Mary Axe a year ago and Bishopsgate last month, City of
London police told security and building managers at a meeting on
contingency planning last night.
Chief Inspector Peter Moore said that the scale of the attacks had changed
the rules for dealing with bombs.
Police no longer recommend evacuating a building in any alert. With acres of
glass poised to fall the street was not necessarily the safest place.
Internal evacuation to a building's core or basement should be considered.
Businesses should liaise over their plans, added Mr Moore. One security
manager said such an exercise in his part of London showed every company
planned to assemble staff in Embankment Gardens - 30,000 people in one small
park.
The police also suggested setting up second locations for all businesses,
fitting shatter-proof film to glass and storing security video tapes.
The possibility of a pager system to alert all City companies to a threat
simultaneously was being considered, he said.
</TEXT>
<XX>
