</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LEADERS of six of Britain's largest trade unions stressed yesterday that
they want to avoid any confrontation with Labour leader Mr John Smith at
this autumn's party conference over the issue of union-party links.
They met yesterday in an attempt to hammer out an agreement on principles
for the relationship between the unions and the Labour party. The leaders
represent the Transport and General Workers, the GMB general union, the
Public Employees, MSF the technicians union, UCW the communications union
and RMT, the main rail union.
The union leaders do not accept one member, one vote for the selection of
Labour parliamentary candidates. They are meeting again next week to try to
find an alternative.
All agreed to back a demand by Mr Bill Morris, the TGWU's general secretary,
for the publication of a joint union statement emphasising why the union
links are essential for the Labour party.
Other union leaders, however, are concerned about a draft of the proposed
statement Mr Morris wants to have approved at today's executive meeting of
Trade Unionists for Labour (TUFL), the party's trade union funding body.
The draft statement says 'Labour's individual membership is small' and those
that belong to the party are 'unrepresentative of Labour voters as a whole'.
The draft says it is 'the affiliated unions that give the party a much
broader, more representative base and a wider appeal among electors'.
The number of women joining unions in Britain rose last year as union
membership fell to less than a third of the employed workforce, statistics
published yesterday in the Employment Gazette show.
In 1992 female union membership rose by 20,000, taking it to 3.7m. Male
membership fell 382,000 to 5.8m.
</TEXT>
