<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 93 / Row delays training revamp
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN OVERHAUL of the education and training of young people, which would
result in all 16-to-19-year-olds working towards a recognised qualification,
is being delayed by a squabble between government departments, the Training
and Enterprise Councils claimed yesterday.
Tec leaders said they had expected Mrs Gillian Shephard, employment
secretary, to publish a white paper on the issue this spring. A working
party - drawn from Tecs, the Department for Education, the Employment
Department and the Further Education Funding Council - submitted a report to
Mrs Shephard, at her request, towards the end of last year.
The working party recommended that by the year 2000 all people up to the age
of 19 should be taking take part in an activity leading to a recognised
qualification. The report called for a strengthened careers guidance service
and a common system of funding for academic, vocational and job-specific
training.
It is understood that the education department favours the proposed reforms
but the Department of Social Security may have objected to a transfer of
funds from its budget to those of other government departments in order to
cover the scheme.
The Engineering Employers' Federation yesterday urged a narrowing of the gap
between academic and vocational training. It put forward a planto the
government for a new national qualification awarded to those who achieved
three Level 3 National Vocational Qualifications, or three A-Levels, or
equivalent units of AS examinations and/or vocational qualifications.
</TEXT>
