<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 93 / Unions back Labour links
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LEADERS of six of Britain's largest trade unions stressed yesterday that
they want to avoid any confrontation with Labour leader Mr John Smith at
this autumn's party conference over the issue of union-party links.
The union leaders, who met yesterday to try to hammer out an agreement on
principles for the future relationship between the unions and the Labour
party, came from the Transport and General Workers, the GMB general union,
the Public Employees, MSF the technicians union, UCW the communications
union and RMT, the main rail union.
The union leaders do not accept one member one vote for the selection of
Labour parliamentary candidates. They are meeting again next week to attempt
to find an alternative.
All agreed to back a demand by Mr Bill Morris, the TGWU's general secretary,
for the publication of a joint union statement to be sent to all Labour
constituency parties and affiliated associations emphasising why the union
links are essential for the Labour party.
Other union leaders, however, are concerned about a draft of the proposed
statement Mr Morris wants to have approved at today's executive meeting of
Trade Unionists for Labour (TUFL), the party's trade union funding body.
The draft statement says 'Labour's individual membership is small' and those
that belong to the party are 'unrepresentative of Labour voters as a whole'.
The statement says it is 'the affiliated unions that give the party a much
broader, more representative base and a wider appeal among electors'.
It says that trade unions are popular, adding: 'It would be foolish to
alienate and lose this base support in the quest for floating voters.'
The statement adds: 'When the media, other parties, business interests and
the establishment have tried to kill off the Labour party the trade unions
have provided the stability which helped us survive.'
One senior union source said of the statement: 'It is unhelpful to Mr John
Smith and potentially divisive.'
</TEXT>
