<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 93 / German union ballot backs wider strikes: Heavy support in
eastern states
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
IG METALL, Germany's engineering union, yesterday received overwhelming
support for further strike action in eastern Germany after balloting metal
and electrical workers in three of the region's states.
More than 82 per cent of the union's 72,000-strong membership in Thuringia,
Berlin-Brandenburg, and Saxony-Anhalt said they were prepared to strike in
pursuit of higher pay.
Backed by such a mandate, the union's leadership, headed by Mr Franz
Steinkuhler, will today hold a special meeting to decide how many more
enterprises in eastern Germany will be targeted for strike action, and where
any action should take place.
Over 40,000 workers from more than 90 enterprises are now on strike to put
pressure on the employers to reinstate a contract signed with the union in
March 1991 which sought to equalise western and eastern wages by next year.
About 10,000 west German workers yesterday held token stoppages in
solidarity with the easterners.
The contract would have meant pay rises exceeding 20 per cent for the metal,
electrical and steel sectors in eastern Germany. But the employers cancelled
the contract because of the country's deteriorating economy.
The threat of further strikes coincides with the resumption today of crucial
talks between the employers and union in the Saxon capital of Dresden.
Mediated by Mr Kurt Biedenkopf, the state's prime minister, they could lead
to a negotiated settlement of the 12-day-old dispute.
Both Mr Dieter Kirchner, head of Gesamtmetall, the metal and electrical
employers association, and Mr Michael Kittner, IG Metall's main legal
expert, will be attending the talks.
</TEXT>
