<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 93 / Key Hungarian's US pay revealed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NICHOLAS DENTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUDAPEST
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Hungarian government faces a politically embarrassing row following
revelations that a US government-financed investment fund has been paying a
large part of the salary of the chairman of Hungary's state holding company.
The Hungarian-American Enterprise Fund (HAEF), the Dollars 60m institution
set up in 1990 to boost the Hungarian private sector, admitted yesterday it
was paying Mr Pal Teleki, chairman of Hungary's state holding company AV RT.
The payment - about Dollars 130,000 (Pounds 84,415) annually - is much
larger than his basic salary.
The admission is expected to anger nationalists, who accuse the conservative
coalition government of favouring foreign investors. The latter, they
allege, have dominated the Hungarian privatisation process to the detriment
of potential local investors.
US companies have been the most active investors in Hungary and confirmation
that the US fund has been subsidising the salary of the man in charge of
about half the country's business sector is expected to cause a political
outcry.
The AV RT controls Hungary's main utilities and the biggest banks and
industrial companies. Its portfolio is worth about Ft1,500bn (Pounds 11bn)
and includes many of the choicest privatisation prospects.
US and Hungarian officials yesterday defended the subsidy as essential for
the AV RT to attract Mr Teleki, a Hungarian-American who formerly worked as
a geologist for the US government.
But several Hungarian officials were critical, saying Mr Teleki's US
connection raised conflict of interest issues.
The exposure of the large payments to Mr Teleki has hit the HAEF at a
vulnerable time. The fund was recently attacked by US congressmen for
allowing its independent merchant bank to pay excessive salaries and make
deals outside its defined area.
</TEXT>
