<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 93 / Street fighters ignore UN pleas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER and Agencies
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE, MOSTAR
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HEAVY street fighting continued yesterday in the south-western Bosnian city
of Mostar, despite attempts by the United Nations to mediate a new ceasefire
between Bosnian Croats and Moslem-led government forces.
Much of the eastern, Moslem-held section of the city was in flames as Croat
troops battled to break a Moslem foothold on the west side of the Neretva
River, which bisects Mostar and which Bosnian Croats want to mark as their
eastern-most boundary.
The Croatian Defense Council (HVO) was holding more than 1,300 Moslem
civilians at the airport building outside Mostar, after forcing them from
their homes, UN officials said yesterday.
Meanwhile, General Philippe Morillon, the UN military commander, met leaders
of the Bosnian army and Bosnian Croat forces in Medjugorje, about 20 km
south-west of Mostar, in an effort to agree a ceasefire. He was also to meet
with Bosnian Croat leader, Mr Mate Boban. In eastern Bosnia, the UN
evacuated the first 22 of about 200 wounded from Zepa, one of six 'safe
areas' declared by the UN security council last week, after Serbs had
blocked the departure of UN helicopters for five hours.
Mr Radovan Karadzic, the Bosnian Serb leader, yesterday said he expected the
inhabitants of his self-styled state would vote against the peace plan to
divide Bosnia into 10 provinces along ethnic lines in this weekend's
referendum.
Bosnian Serbs have turned down a call by the Serbian president, Mr Slobodan
Milosevic, to attend a joint session of an 'all Serbian' parliament to
ratify the UN peace plan.
They opted instead to go ahead with the referendum on the UN proposal.
Serbia has imposed sanctions on the Bosnian Serbs for refusing to back the
plan.
</TEXT>
