<HEADLINE>
FT  13 MAY 93 / Political polecat treats Danes to a Maastricht mauling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY and HILARY BARNES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   COPENHAGEN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE BRITISH hijacked Denmark's Maastricht referendum contest yesterday to
the bemusement - and some irritation - of the Danes.
British politicians, trailed by British camera crews and British reporters,
traded insults and doled out advice to the Danes in the ante-chambers of the
Folketing, the Danish parliament - all in English of course.
In one corner was Lord Tebbit, erstwhile Conservative cabinet minister,
scourge of Maastricht and political street-fighter of repute. Lord Tebbit
was invited to Copenhagen by the June Movement, fellow-travellers
campaigning for a repeat of last June's No vote in Denmark.
In the other, seeking to blunt whatever impact Lord Tebbit might have, was
the scholarly Mr Giles Radice, Labour MP, more sheepdog than polecat, and
guest of the governing Social Democratic party.
Lord Tebbit, Mr Radice warned at a press conference, was a 'xenophobic
meddler' with no genuine concern for Denmark. The referendum, he said
earnestly, was 'not something the British should interfere with at all',
glossing over what Mr Radice was doing in Denmark himself.
Summoning up a look of injured indignation, Lord Tebbit protested. His
objections to Maastricht were based not on xenophobia but on a belief that
it would do great damage to the European Community. 'Is it meddling to tell
the Danish people what I as a European citizen believe?' he asked reasonably
enough. 'Are we to have free movement of goods but thought police at our
borders?'
It is a moot point what effect - if any - such interventions will have on
Tuesday's vote. A Gallup poll to be published today showed that the
long-standing Yes lead was hardening. It showed 49 per cent in favour and 33
per cent against, compared with a gap of 46-34 at the weekend, with 14 per
cent undecided and the balance resolved not to vote. Another poll, also to
be published today, showed 52 per cent in favour, 36 per cent against, 8 per
cent undecided and 4 per cent resolved not to vote.
The respected pro-Maastricht newspaper Berlingske Tidende had sharp words
for the British visitors, also taking a swipe at Sir James Goldsmith,
financier turned crusader, who has paid for full-page advertisements in
Danish newspapers advocating a No vote.
The British, said Berlingske Tidende, 'are not welcome to consider the vote
as a substitute for the referendum which they themselves will not have, let
alone treat the Danish voters as puppets who can be used to vote no for
reasons of British domestic politics'.
Ulterior motive or no, Lord Tebbit said a second Danish No vote would stop
British ratification of Maastricht and that Denmark would not subsequently
be isolated or pushed out of the European Community. Yes campaign propaganda
to that effect played on 'fear, ignorance and sheer misstatement of facts',
added Britain's most celebrated Maastricht mauler.
Punks and pensioners find common cause, Page 3
</TEXT>
