<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow stages late surge on
program buying
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
AFTER drifting in narrow trading ranges for most of the day, US stocks ended
with solid gains yesterday, thanks to a late burst of program buying, writes
Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 25.47 at 3,468.75,
having spent almost the entire day only a few points above opening values.
The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 moved in similar fashion,
finishing 1.56 ahead at 444.36, while the Nasdaq composite was 0.24 firmer
at 683.06. Trading volume on the New York SE totalled 221.5m shares, while
rises outpaced declines by 1,059 to 859.
Once again the absence of fresh economic news, or a lead from either
overseas equity markets or from a becalmed US bond market, left investors
searching for inspiration at the opening. Although prices rose sharply on
Monday morning, the buying was mostly technical in nature and by the end of
the day the Dow had registered a gain of only 6 points, which meant that the
markets' main index had barely moved for five trading days - a reflection of
investors' uncertainty about the outlook for the economy, corporate earnings
and stock prices.
This pattern was maintained for most of the day, with many investors
deciding to sit on the sidelines, at least until the next piece of economic
data - today's release of the April producer prices index. The Dow and the S
&amp; P suddenly took off, however, in the final hour of trading as computerised
buy programs lifted a range of leading stocks.
Anheuser Busch, the largest brewer in the US, climbed Dollars 1 7/8 to
Dollars 51 3/4 in busy trading on reports that beer may be exempted from
President Bill Clinton's proposed 'sin' taxes, which are likely to be levied
on cigarette and liquor sales.
Philip Morris, owner of the company which makes Miller Beer, the main
domestic competitor to Anheuser Busch's Budweiser brands, failed to receive
a lift from the news. Its shares declined Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 51 1/2 ,
primarily because of profit-taking in the wake of recent gains by the stock.
Bank shares were in favour as a group, posting gains across the board.
Citicorp added Dollars  1/2 at Dollars 28 1/4 , Chemical Dollars 1 3/8 at
Dollars 39 5/8 and Chase Manhattan Dollars 1 1/8 at Dollars 31.
On the Nasdaq market, technology stocks ran into sellers. Intel fell Dollars
3 to Dollars 99 1/2 on 3.7m shares traded after brokerage Kidder Peabody
lowered its investment rating on the stock from 'buy' to 'accumulate'.
Canada
TORONTO closed marginally higher as a rally in gold issues, underpinned by a
recovery in bullion futures prices, pulled the market up from earlier losses
and offset weakness in banking shares. Dealers said the overall tone was
lacklustre as the market consolidates from several months of gains and heavy
volumes.
The TSE 300 index was finally up 1.8 at 3,780.4 and rises led falls by 355
to 344. Turnover was 54.9m shares.
Thomson Corp slipped CDollars  1/4 to CDollars 15 3/8 . The company said Mr
Michael W. Johnston resigned as chief executive of Thomson Newspapers, one
of Thomson Corp's three major operating units.
</TEXT>
