FT  12 MAY 93 / International Company News: Pentagon warns on C-17 project
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A TOP Pentagon official yesterday warned McDonnell Douglas, the defence
contractor, that unless it improved its development of the C-17 transport
aircraft, the programme would be cancelled, writes Martin Dickson.
The company had been hoping for a 120-aircraft order, worth up to Dollars
40bn or more. However, the project has been subject to delays and cost
overruns.
Mr John Deutch, under-secretary of defence for acquisition, said in a letter
to the company that 'unless there is strong resolve on the part of McDonnell
Douglas corporate management to meet contract requirements, particularly
schedule specifications and testing requirements, the C-17 cannot be
continued.'
McDonnell said it was confident the programme was viable and would result in
production of the aircraft.
