<HEADLINE>
FT  12 MAY 93 / International Company News: FASB rule would cut earnings,
study says
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HIGH-TECH companies in the US face a 49.5 per cent reduction in earnings if
a recently-proposed accounting ruling is approved, according to a study
released today by Wyatt Company, a leading consulting firm in employee
benefits.
Companies outside the high-tech sector would see earnings decline by a more
modest 5.8 per cent, the study found.
The survey comes as the Financial Accounting Standards Board (FASB) prepares
its official draft of new rules governing the disclosure and accounting
methods for share options. The proposed measures would make companies report
the value of share options granted to employees and deduct them from
profits.
Wyatt based its findings on a survey of 139 companies in the high-tech,
service and minerals/manufacturing sectors. It found the median option value
at high-tech companies was 58.8 per cent of the actual stock price on the
date of the option grant, against 35.9 per cent for other companies.
In addition, the average high-tech company grants nearly five times as may
options to employees as other companies.
If the FASB proposal goes ahead in its present form, most companies outside
the high-tech sector will not alter their stock-option policies, said Wyatt.
'Apparently, most of these companies assume that sophisticated financial
analysts will look beyond this expense in assessing company performance,
value and potential,' said Mr Matt Ward, a Wyatt consultant.
Wyatt's findings may give weight to critics of the FASB proposal who claim
it will have a disproportionate impact on start-up companies with little
working capital.
FASB will release its official draft in June. If adopted, the full proposal
would not take effect before 1997.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
